I cloned your repository and made sure that the upstream remote points to Bioconductor

$ git remote -v
...
upstream	git at git.bioconductor.org:packages/DMCHMM (fetch)
upstream	git at git.bioconductor.org:packages/DMCHMM (push)

I then made a local branch from the upstream branch

git checkout -b RELEASE_3_14 upstream/RELEASE_3_14

I then looked for differences between the RELEASE_3_14 and master branches

git diff --stat RELEASE_3_14 master
 DESCRIPTION         | 2 +-
 R/findDMCs-method.R | 7 ++++---
 2 files changed, 5 insertions(+), 4 deletions(-)

and I see that there are changes in two files. In more detail, from the output of

git diff RELEASE_3_14 master

I see that the DESCRIPTION difference is version bump, and the change in R/findDMCs-method.R is I guess the change that you'd like to make.

Is that what you see? If so it means that you need to make (or copy) the same changes on the release branch as on the master branch, but using the correct version bump. I did this manually, by checking out the RELEASE_3_14 branch and updating according to the diff; there are much more clever ways of doing this... After making and committing the changes, I see

$ git diff --stat master
